FRANCISCO
INTERNATIONAL
AIRPORT
INNER ROADS
The sketch at left shows the elevated inner road, a new 3-lane
structure to provide express lanes for the departure level of
the airport. This will allow more curb space for drop-off on
the terminal road and ease congestion - allowing "thru"
traffic to move on the inner road loop, either to destinations
Turtner downstream or to leave the complex.
RAPID TRANSIT
The continuing rapid growth of the San Francisco International
Airport shows that ground access improvements are a major
need. It is clear that rapid transit service must be provided if
the airport is to reach its optimum regional use as an air-ground
transportation transfer point without falling to vehicular
access restrictions.
An extension of BART from Daly City to a stub-end station at
the upper level of the Terminal and Transportation Center is
tunctionally teasible but not vet approved or tinanced.
The top photo shows a possible airport interchange at Bayshore
Freeway which weaves auto and rapid transit structures into a
sweeping entry design that leads into the Terminal complex.
The second picture is a mezzanine level plan of the future
Terminal and Transportation Center which could accommodate
BART. A vehicular people mover system is shown on the main
concourse below.
